qdma: ack all pending IRQ causes, not just the enabled ones

en75_irq_handler masked the int_status read to the driver's enabled bits
*before* writing it back to the (write-1-to-clear) status register. Causes the
driver leaves disabled but that the hardware still latches are therefore never
acked. On the EN751221 the TX "no descriptor" cause (bit 2) is asserted
whenever a TX ring sits idle and is not in the enabled mask, so it is never
cleared: the shared QDMA IRQ line stays high and storms ~31k spurious irq21/s
on the CPU that services RX. That steals the RX CPU continuously and adds
multi-millisecond, jittery latency to every forwarded/terminated packet (ping
to the device: min 0.6 ms but avg 5-6 ms / max 10-27 ms).

Fix: ack the full pending status first (it is write-1-to-clear), then mask to
the enabled bits for processing. Idle irq21 drops from ~31k/s to the real
packet rate.

--- a/econet_qdma.c
+++ b/econet_qdma.c
@@ -532,11 +532,16 @@ static irqreturn_t en75_irq_handler(int irq_num, void *dev_instance)
 		u32 disable_int = 0;
 		u8 bit;

 		regval = en75_rreg(irq->status_reg[i]);
-		regval &= irq->irqmask[i];

-		/* You must write the bits back to the status register
-		 * or you will keep receiving the same interrupt. */
+		/* Status is write-1-to-clear: ack ALL pending causes first,
+		 * then mask to the enabled ones below. Some causes the driver
+		 * leaves disabled stay latched in hardware (notably TX NO_DSCP
+		 * while a TX ring is idle); writing back only the enabled bits
+		 * never clears them, so the shared IRQ line stays asserted and
+		 * storms (~31k spurious irq21/s on the RX CPU), starving it
+		 * and adding multi-ms forwarding/ping jitter. */
 		en75_wreg((u32)regval, irq->status_reg[i]);
+		regval &= irq->irqmask[i];

 		for_each_set_bit(bit, &regval, 32) {
